1. Rewrite the denominator as a difference of two terms: $(1 + \sqrt{2}) - \sqrt{3}$.

2. Multiply both the numerator and denominator by the conjugate of the denominator: $(1 + \sqrt{2}) + \sqrt{3}$.

$$\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{1 + \sqrt{2} - \sqrt{3}} & = \frac{1}{(1 + \sqrt{2}) - \sqrt{3}} \times \frac{(1 + \sqrt{2}) + \sqrt{3}}{(1 + \sqrt{2}) + \sqrt{3}} \\
& = \frac{(1 + \sqrt{2}) + \sqrt{3}}{(1 + \sqrt{2})^2 - (\sqrt{3})^2}
\end{align*}$$

3. Simplify the denominator:

$$\begin{align*}
\frac{(1 + \sqrt{2}) + \sqrt{3}}{(1 + \sqrt{2})^2 - (\sqrt{3})^2} & = \frac{1 + \sqrt{2} + \sqrt{3}}{(1 + 2\sqrt{2} + 2) - 3} \\
& = \frac{1 + \sqrt{2} + \sqrt{3}}{2\sqrt{2}}
\end{align*}$$

4. Rationalize the denominator by multiplying both the numerator and denominator by $\sqrt{2}$:

$$\begin{align*}
\frac{1 + \sqrt{2} + \sqrt{3}}{2\sqrt{2}} & = \frac{1 + \sqrt{2} + \sqrt{3}}{2\sqrt{2}} \times \frac{\sqrt{2}}{\sqrt{2}} \\
& = \frac{\sqrt{2} + 2 + \sqrt{6}}{4}
\end{align*}$$

