The key insight to solve this problem is to recognize that the desired area can be calculated by subtracting the area of the smaller circle from the area of the larger circle. This works because the circles are concentric, meaning they share the same center point.
Step 1: Calculate the area of the smaller circle using the formula $A = \pi r^2$.
$$\begin{align*}
A_1 &= \pi r_1^2 \\
    &= \pi (1)^2 \\
    &= \pi \text{ square inches}
\end{align*}$$

Step 2: Calculate the area of the larger circle using the same formula.
$$\begin{align*}
A_2 &= \pi r_2^2 \\
    &= \pi (10)^2 \\
    &= 100\pi \text{ square inches}
\end{align*}$$

Step 3: Subtract the area of the smaller circle from the area of the larger circle to find the desired area.
$$\begin{align*}
A_{\text{desired}} &= A_2 - A_1 \\
                    &= 100\pi - \pi \\
                    &= 99\pi \text{ square inches}
\end{align*}$$
The area of the region outside the smaller circle but inside the larger circle is $99\pi$ square inches.
